To identify your router and gateway ip addresses
khumbulani@kartoza:~$ route -n
Kernel IP routing table
Destination     Gateway         Genmask         Flags Metric Ref    Use Iface

khumbulani@kartoza:~$ route
Kernel IP routing table
Destination     Gateway         Genmask         Flags Metric Ref    Use Iface

khumbulani@kartoza:~$ netstat -nr
Kernel IP routing table
Destination     Gateway         Genmask         Flags   MSS Window  irtt Iface
khumbulani@kartoza:~$ ping -c 4 ip_address
PING 0.0.0.0 (0.0.0.0) 56(84) bytes of data.
64 bytes from 0.0.0.0: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=0.361 ms
64 bytes from 0.0.0.0: icmp_seq=2 ttl=64 time=0.304 ms
64 bytes from 0.0.2.1: icmp_seq=3 ttl=64 time=0.286 ms
64 bytes from 0.0.0.0: icmp_seq=4 ttl=64 time=0.293 ms

--- 0.0.0.0 ping statistics ---
4 packets transmitted, 4 received, 0% packet loss, time 2998ms
rtt min/avg/max/mdev = 0.286/0.311/0.361/0.029 ms

http://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/how-to-find-gateway-ip-address/

To identify your public ip address,do one of these:

curl ident.me

curl ifconfig.me

curl tnx.nl/ip

curl icanhazip.com

curl ipecho.net/plain

curl ip.appspot.com

curl whatsmyip.akamai.com

http://www.yourownlinux.com/2014/01/how-to-determine-your-public-ip-address-from-linux-terminal.html
